Handling events for a swimlane graph involves using interactive graph libraries (like ngx-graph, JointJS, or Cytoscape)
to detect user actions—such as clicks, double-clicks, hovers, or drag-and-drop—on nodes, edges, or the lanes themselves.
Implement these by binding event listeners to the graph elements and capturing (click) or (dblclick) events within SVG
nodes or container divs to trigger actions.

## Key Techniques for Handling Swimlane Events:

- Node/Task Interaction (Click/Double-Click): Bind click event handlers to task nodes to display detailed information or
  launch a dialogue. In ngx-graph, this is done via <svg:g class="node" (click)="onNodeClick($event)">.
- Drag-and-Drop (Updating Ownership): Implement drag-and-drop to move tasks between lanes. The event handler should
  identify the new lane and update the underlying data model to change the responsible party.
- Hover Events (Tooltips): Use hover (or mouseover) events on nodes or connection lines to display tooltips or highlight
  connected steps.
- Contextual Menus: Add right-click (contextmenu) events on nodes to allow users to delete, edit, or split tasks.
- Lane Selection/Highlighting: Allow users to click on a lane header to highlight all tasks within that specific
  department or role.

## Common Events to Handle:

- onNodeClick: Select a task.
- onNodeDoubleCLick: Open task details.
- onEdgeClick: Select a connector/flow.
- onLayoutChange: Triggered when the diagram structure updates.

